wn’s work, situating her scholarship in relation to some of the major thinkers and methodologies of the Frankfurt School. Brown opens the discussion with a new essay expounding upon the meaning of freedom and the prospects for emancipation in our current political moment. Subsequent chapters address different aspects of Brown’s corpus, including her early feminist interpretation of the history of political theory, her influential critiques of identity politics and progressive philosophies of history, and her recent interrogation of the rise of neoliberalism and the resurgence of authoritarian politics. The volume concludes with Brown’s response to her critics, where she clarifies and expands upon the implications of her core ideas.In addition to Brown and the editors, the contributors to this volume include Robin Celikates, Loren Goldman, Asad Haider, Robyn Marasco, and Johanna Oksala.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCritical theory. 0aFeminist theory. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aPower (Social sciences). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh  aFrankfurt School.  aWendy Brown.  acritical theory for undergraduate students.  acurrent prospects for emancipation.  aidea of progress.  aneoliberalism.  aresurgence of authoritarian politics.  aright-wing populism.1 aAllen, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCelikates, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldman, Loren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaider, Asad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarasco, Robyn, 